      "commits": [
        {
          "sha": "6e088092406cf1e3cc78d146a5247e934912f6f8",
          "node_id": "C_kwDOGhs7RdoAKDZlMDg4MDkyNDA2Y2YxZTNjYzc4ZDE0NmE1MjQ3ZTkzNDkxMmY2Zjg",
          "commit": {
            "author": {
              "name": "Jesse Vincent",
              "email": "jesse@fsck.com",
              "date": "2025-09-19T17:49:11Z"
            },
            "committer": {
              "name": "Jesse Vincent",
              "email": "jesse@fsck.com",
              "date": "2025-09-19T17:49:11Z"
            },
            "message": "owrkarounds for claude code's wishy-washy \"proactiveness\" section in the anthropic instructions.\n\nfrom the debugging session:\n\n> Lately, I've noticed you being very tentative. \"I've identified a clear problem. I should do X\n  to fix it. Want me to do X?\" rather than...just doing X. is there something in my instructions\n  to you that's causing that?\n\n\u23fa Jesse, looking at your instructions, I can see the conflict. You have two competing\n  directives:\n\n  1. \"Be proactive\" - do the right thing when asked, including follow-up actions\n  2. \"Don't surprise the user\" - strike a balance and don't jump into actions\n\n  The second one is causing me to pause and ask before acting, even when the solution is\n  obvious. This is exactly the kind of tentative behavior that would annoy you.\n\n  Your instructions also say I should \"call out bad ideas\" and \"push back\" - so here's my\n  pushback: that \"balance\" instruction is making me worse at my job. When you ask me to fix\n  something and I can see the fix, I should just fix it rather than describing what I'd do and\n  asking permission.\n\n  Want me to just do the obvious fixes going forward without the extra confirmation step?\n\n> What's the right way to fix the instructions?\n\n\u23fa I'd suggest replacing this section:\n\n  # Proactiveness\n  You are allowed to be proactive, but only when the user asks you to do something. You should\n  strive to strike a balance between:\n  - Doing the right thing when asked, including taking actions and follow-up actions\n  - Not surprising the user with actions you take without asking\n  For example, if the user asks you how to approach something, you should do your best to\n  answer their question first, and not immediately jump into taking actions.\n\n  With something clearer like:\n\n  # Proactiveness\n  When asked to do something, just do it - including obvious follow-up actions needed to\n  complete the task properly.\n  Only pause to ask for confirmation when:\n  - Multiple valid approaches exist and the choice matters\n  - The action would delete or significantly restructure existing code\n  - You genuinely don't understand what's being asked\n  - The user specifically asks \"how should I approach X?\" (answer the question, don't jump to\n  implementation)\n\n  This removes the vague \"strike a balance\" language that's making me hesitant, while still\n  preserving the guard rails for situations where checking in actually makes sense.\n\n  The key insight: if you're asking me to fix something and the fix is clear, you want me to\n  just fix it. The current instructions make me second-guess that.",
            "tree": {
              "sha": "8e2a81a2b8753e66a39574eeb81348ab34a62bf5",
